===Objective===

The Apollo 13 mission was to explore the [[Fra Mauro formation]], or Fra Mauro highlands, named after the 80-kilometer-diameter [[Fra Mauro crater]] located within it. It is a widespread, hilly [[selenology|selenological]] area thought to be composed of ejecta from the impact that formed [[Mare Imbrium]].

The next Apollo mission, Apollo 14, eventually made a successful flight to Fra Mauro.

===Oxygen tank rupture===
April 14, 1970, 03:07:53 [[UTC]] (April 13, 21:07:53 [[Central Standard Time (North America)|CST]], 55:54:53 Ground Elapsed Time);<ref name="timeline">{{cite book |last=Orloff |first=Richard W. |title=Apollo by the Numbers: A Statistical Reference |url=http://history.nasa.gov/SP-4029/SP-4029.htm |accessdate=December 31, 2012 |series=NASA History Series |origyear=First published 2000 |year=2004 |month=September |work=NASA History Division, Office of Policy and Plans |publisher=NASA |location=Washington, D.C. |isbn=0-16-050631-X |lccn=00-061677 |id=NASA SP-2000-4029 |chapter=Apollo 13 Timeline |chapterurl=http://history.nasa.gov/SP-4029/Apollo_13h_Timeline.htm}}</ref> {{convert|173790.5|nmi|km|0|abbr=on}} from [[Earth]]<ref name="Rumerman">{{cite book |last=Rumerman |first=Judith A. |others=Updated by Chris Gamble and Gabriel Okolski |title=U.S. Human Spaceflight: A Record of Achievement, 1961–2006 |url=http://history.nasa.gov/monograph41.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=July 3, 2013 |edition=Rev. |series=Monographs in Aerospace History |issue=No. 41 |origyear=First published 1998 |year=2007 |month=December |publisher=NASA History Division |location=Washington, D.C. |lccn=2007022208 |id=NASA SP-2007-4541 |page=26}}</ref>

===Closest approach to Moon===
April 15, 1970, 00:21:00 UTC; {{convert|137|nmi|km|1|abbr=on}}<ref name="Orloff13">{{cite book |last=Orloff |first=Richard W. |title=Apollo by the Numbers: A Statistical Reference |url=http://history.nasa.gov/SP-4029/SP-4029.htm |accessdate=JJuly 3, 2013 |series=NASA History Series |origyear=First published 2000 |year=2004 |month=September |work=NASA History Division, Office of Policy and Plans |publisher=NASA |location=Washington, D.C. |isbn=0-16-050631-X |lccn=00-061677 |id=NASA SP-2000-4029 |chapter=Apollo 13 - The Seventh Mission: The Third Lunar Landing Attempt |chapterurl=http://history.nasa.gov/SP-4029/Apollo_13a_Summary.htm}}</ref>

===Splashdown===
April 17, 1970, 18:07:41 UTC (142:54:47 Ground Elapsed Time). Crew was on board the [[USS Iwo Jima (LPH-2)|USS ''Iwo Jima'']] 45 minutes later.

==Mission highlights==

===Launch and translunar injection===
[[File:Apollo 13 liftoff-KSC-70PC-160HR.jpg|thumb|left|Apollo 13 launches from Kennedy Space Center, April 11, 1970]]
[[File:2010-06-11 CSM&LM.jpg|right|thumb|250px|Apollo 13 spacecraft configuration en route to the Moon]]

The mission was launched at the planned time, 02:13:00 PM [[Eastern Standard Time (North America)|EST]] (19:13:00 UTC) on April 11. An anomaly occurred when the second-stage, center (inboard) engine shut down about two minutes early. The four outboard engines and the third-stage engine burned longer to compensate, and the vehicle achieved very close to the planned circular {{convert|100|nmi|km}} parking orbit, followed by a normal translunar injection about two hours later.<ref name="lver" /><ref>{{cite book |last1=Benson |first1=Charles D. |last2=Faherty |first2=William Barnaby |title=Moonport: A History of Apollo Launch Facilities and Operations |url=http://www.hq.nasa.gov/office/pao/History/SP-4204/contents.html |accessdate=July 3, 2013 |year=1978 |publisher=NASA |id=NASA SP-4204 |chapter=Apollo 14 Launch Operations |chapterurl=http://www.hq.nasa.gov/office/pao/History/SP-4204/ch22-7.html}} Ch.22-7. Comments on Apollo 13 pogo.</ref> The engine shutdown was determined to be caused by severe [[pogo oscillation]]s measured at a strength of 68 ''g'' and a frequency of 16 hertz, flexing the thrust frame by {{convert|3|in|mm}}. The vehicle's guidance system shut the engine down in response to sensed thrust chamber pressure fluctuations. Pogo oscillations had been seen on previous Titan rockets, and also on the Saturn V during [[Apollo 6]],<ref>{{cite journal |last=Fenwick |first=Jim |year=1992 |month=Spring |title=Pogo |url=http://web.archive.org/web/20071213010936/http://www.engineeringatboeing.com/articles/pogo.htm |journal=Threshold |publisher=[[Pratt & Whitney Rocketdyne]] |accessdate=July 3, 2013}}</ref> but on Apollo 13 they were amplified by an unexpected interaction with turbopump [[cavitation]].<ref>{{cite journal |last=Dotson |first=Kirk |year=2003/2004 |month=Winter |title=Mitigating Pogo on Liquid-Fueled Rockets |journal=Crosslink |volume=5 |issue=1 |pages=26–29 |location=El Segundo, CA |publisher=[[The Aerospace Corporation]] |format=PDF |accessdate=July 3, 2013 |url=http://aerospace.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/crosslink/V5N1.pdf}}</ref> Later missions implemented anti-pogo modifications that had been under development. These included addition of a helium gas reservoir to the center engine [[liquid oxygen]] line to dampen pressure oscillations, an automatic cutoff as a backup, and simplification of the propellant valves of all five second-stage engines.

The crew performed the separation and transposition maneuver to dock the Command Module ''Odyssey'' to the [[Apollo Lunar Module|Lunar Module]] (LM) ''Aquarius'', and pulled away from the spent third stage, which ground controllers then sent on a course to impact the Moon in range of a seismometer placed on surface by [[Apollo 12]]. They then settled in for the three-day trip to Fra Mauro.
{{clear}}
===Oxygen tank incident===
[[File:Apollo 13 timeline.svg|center|thumb|550px|Apollo 13's complete circumlunar flight trajectory drawn to scale, showing its distance to the Moon when the accident occurred|The [[circumlunar trajectory]] followed by Apollo 13; the accident occurred about 5½ hours from entry into the Moon's sphere of gravitational influence]]

{{Listen|filename=Apollo13-wehaveaproblem.ogg|title=Houston, we've had a problem.|description=Swigert and Lovell reporting the incident on April 14, 1970|format=[[Ogg]]}}

En route to the Moon, approximately {{convert|200000|mi|km}} from Earth,{{Citation needed|date=November 2013}} [[Lyndon B. Johnson Space Center|Mission Control]] asked Swigert to turn on the hydrogen and oxygen tank stirring fans, which were designed to destratify the [[cryogenic]] contents and increase the accuracy of their quantity readings. Approximately 93 seconds later, just under 56 hours since launch, the astronauts heard a "loud bang," accompanied by fluctuations in electrical power and firing of the attitude control thrusters.<ref name="timeline" /> The crew initially thought that a [[meteoroid]] might have struck the Lunar Module.

[[File:Mission Operations Control Room during Apollo 13.jpg|thumb|Overall view of the Mission Operations Control Room during Apollo 13's fourth television transmission, on the evening of April 13, 1970. Astronaut Fred Haise, Jr., Lunar Module Pilot, is seen on the screen]]
In fact, the number-2 oxygen tank, one of two in the Service Module, had exploded.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ntrs.nasa.gov/archive/nasa/casi.ntrs.nasa.gov/19700076776_1970076776.pdf |title=Report of Apollo 13 Review Board |last=Cortright |first=Edgar M. |authorlink=Edgar Cortright |date=June 15, 1970 |publisher=NASA |location=Washington, D.C. |format=PDF}} Text ([[Text file#.TXT|.TXT]]) file of report [http://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/planetary/lunar/apollo_13_review_board.txt here]. Multi-part PDF files of the report are available [http://history.nasa.gov/ap13rb/ap13index.htm here] and [http://drushel.cwru.edu/apollo13/ here]. Note that NASA's official report does not itself use the word "explosion" in describing the tank rupture. See [http://history.nasa.gov/ap13rb/ch5.pdf findings 26 and 27] (PDF) on page 195 (5-22) of the NASA report.</ref> Damaged [[Polytetrafluoroethylene|Teflon]] insulation on the wires to the stirring fan inside oxygen tank 2 allowed the wires to [[short circuit|short-circuit]] and ignite this insulation. The resulting fire rapidly increased pressure beyond its {{convert|1000|psi|MPa}} limit and the tank dome failed, filling the fuel cell bay (Sector 4) with rapidly expanding gaseous oxygen and combustion products. It is also possible some combustion occurred of the [[Mylar]]/[[Kapton]] thermal insulation material used to line the oxygen shelf compartment in this bay.<ref name="report">{{Citation |last=Cortright |first=Edgar M. |title=Report of the Apollo 13 Review Board |date=June 15, 1970 |url=http://ntrs.nasa.gov/archive/nasa/casi.ntrs.nasa.gov/19700076776_1970076776.pdf |publisher=NASA |location=Washington, D.C. |format=PDF}} Text (.TXT) file of report [http://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/planetary/lunar/apollo_13_review_board.txt here]. Multi-part PDF files of the report are available [http://history.nasa.gov/ap13rb/ap13index.htm here] and [http://drushel.cwru.edu/apollo13/ here].</ref>

The resulting pressure inside the compartment popped the bolts attaching the 13-foot Sector-4 outer aluminum skin panel, which as it blew off probably caused minor damage to the nearby high-gain [[Unified S-band|S-band]] antenna used for translunar communications. Communications and telemetry to Earth were lost for 1.8 seconds, until the system automatically corrected by switching the antenna from narrow-band to wide-band mode.

[[Shock (mechanics)|Mechanical shock]] forced the oxygen valves closed on the number-1 and number-3 fuel cells, leaving them operating for only about three minutes on the oxygen in the feed lines. The shock also either partially ruptured a line from the number-1 oxygen tank, or caused its check or relief valve to leak, causing its contents to leak out into space over the next 130 minutes, entirely depleting the SM's oxygen supply.<ref name="report" />

Because the fuel cells combined hydrogen and oxygen to generate electricity and water, the remaining fuel cell number 2 finally shut down and left the Command Module on limited-duration battery power. The crew was forced to shut down the CM completely and to use the LM as a "lifeboat."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/nmc/masterCatalog.do?sc=1970-029A |title=Apollo 13 Command and Service Module (CSM) |work=[[National Space Science Data Center]] |publisher=NASA |accessdate=October 31, 2009}}</ref> This situation had been suggested during an earlier training simulation, but had not been considered a likely scenario.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lovell |first1=Jim |authorlink1=Jim Lovell |last2=Kluger |first2=Jeffrey |authorlink2=Jeffrey Kluger |title=[[Lost Moon|Apollo 13]] |origyear=Previously published 1994 as ''[[Lost Moon]]'' |year=2000 |publisher=[[Houghton Mifflin Harcourt|Houghton Mifflin Company]] |location=Boston |isbn=0-618-05665-3 |lccn=99089647 |pages=83–87}}</ref> Without the LM, the accident would certainly have been fatal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/nmc/masterCatalog.do?sc=1970-029C|title=Apollo 13 Lunar Module/ALSEP|work=National Space Science Data Center |publisher=NASA|accessdate=October 31, 2009}}</ref>

===Crew survival and return journey===
[[File:Direct Abort Trajectory - Lunar Landing Symposium, MSC Jun66.jpg|left|thumb|250px|A Direct Abort return, depicted in a 1966 planning report, was not viable by the time of the accident, as it required jettisoning the [[Apollo Lunar Module|Lunar Module]] "lifeboat". The trajectory shown is at a point much earlier than where the accident happened.]]

The damage to the Service Module made safe return from a lunar landing impossible, so Lead Flight Director [[Gene Kranz]] aborted the mission. The existing abort plans, first drawn up in 1966, were evaluated; the quickest was a Direct Abort trajectory, which required using the Service Module Propulsion System (SPS) engine to achieve a {{convert|6079|ft/s|m/s|adj=on}} change in velocity.<ref name = "missionopreport"/><sup>p.&nbsp;III-14</sup> Although a successful SPS firing at 60 hours GET would land the crew one day earlier (at 118 hours GET, or 58 hours later), the large delta v was only possible if the LM were jettisoned first,<ref name = "missionopreport"/><sup>p.&nbsp;II-1</sup> and since crew survival depended on the LM's presence during the coast back to Earth, that option was "out of the question."<ref name = "missionopreport"/><sup>p.&nbsp;III-17</sup> Apollo 13 was close to entering the lunar [[sphere of influence (astrodynamics)|sphere of influence]] (at 61 hours GET), which was the break-even point between direct and circumlunar aborts, and the latter allowed more time for evaluation and planning before a major rocket burn.<ref name = "missionopreport"/><sup>p. B-5</sup> There also was concern about "the structural integrity of the Service Module,"<ref name = "missionopreport"/><sup>p.&nbsp;III‑23</sup> so mission planners were instructed that the SPS engine would not be used "except as a last-ditch effort."<ref name = "missionopreport"/><sup>p.&nbsp;III-14</sup>

For these reasons, Kranz chose the circumlunar option, using the Moon's gravity to return the ship to Earth. However, Apollo 13 had left its initial [[free-return trajectory]] earlier in the mission, as required for the planned lunar landing at Fra Mauro. Therefore, the first order of business was to re-establish the free-return trajectory with a 30.7-sec. burn of the LM [[Descent Propulsion System]]. The descent engine was used again two hours after [[pericynthion]], the closest approach to the Moon ("PC+2 burn"), to speed the return to Earth by 10 hours and move the landing spot from the Indian Ocean to the Pacific Ocean. A more aggressive burn could have been performed at PC+2 by first jettisoning the Service Module, returning the crew in about the same amount of time as a direct abort,<ref name = "missionopreport"/><sup>p.&nbsp;III-20</sup> but this was deemed unnecessary given the rates at which consumables were being used. The 4-min. 24-sec. burn was so accurate that only two more small course corrections were subsequently needed.

[[File:Apollo13 apparatus.jpg|thumb|Astronaut John L. Swigert, at right, with the "mailbox" rig improvised to adapt the Command Module's square [[carbon dioxide]] scrubber cartridges to fit the Lunar Module, which took a round cartridge]]
[[File:Apollo 13 Mailbox at Mission Control.jpg|thumb|left|250px|The "mailbox" at [[Mission Control#NASA Mission Control Center|Mission Control]] during the Apollo 13 mission]]
Considerable ingenuity under extreme pressure was required from the crew, [[flight controller]]s, and support personnel for the safe return. The developing drama was shown on television.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.museum.tv/eotvsection.php?entrycode=spaceprogram |title=Space Program and Television |last=Paterson |first=Chris |publisher=[[Museum of Broadcast Communications]] |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20101204055730/http://www.museum.tv/eotvsection.php?entrycode=spaceprogram |archivedate=December 4, 2010 |accessdate=October 30, 2009}}</ref> Because electrical power was severely limited, no more live TV broadcasts were made; TV commentators used models and animated footage as illustrations. Low power levels made even voice communications difficult.

The Lunar Module consumables were intended to sustain two people for a day and a half, not three people for four days. Oxygen was the least critical consumable because the LM carried enough to repressurize the LM after each surface [[Extra-vehicular activity|EVA]]. Unlike the [[Apollo Command/Service Module|Command/Service Module]] (CSM), which was powered by fuel cells that produced water as a byproduct, the LM was powered by [[Silver-oxide battery|silver-zinc batteries]], so electrical power and water (used for equipment cooling as well as drinking) were critical consumables. To keep the LM life-support and communication systems operational until re-entry, the LM was powered down to the lowest levels possible. In particular, the LM's [[Abort Guidance System]] was used for most of the coast back to Earth instead of the primary guidance system, as it used less power and water.<ref name = "missionopreport"/><sup>pp.&nbsp;III‑17,33,40</sup>

Availability of [[lithium hydroxide]] (LiOH) for [[carbon dioxide scrubber|removing carbon dioxide]] presented a serious problem. The LM's internal stock of LiOH canisters was not sufficient to support the crew until return, and the remainder was stored in the descent stage, out of reach. The CM had an adequate supply of canisters, but these were incompatible with the LM. Engineers on the ground improvised a way to join the cube-shaped CM canisters to the LM's cylindrical canister-sockets by drawing air through them with a suit return hose. The astronauts called the jury-rigged device "the mailbox."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://grin.hq.nasa.gov/ABSTRACTS/GPN-2002-000056.html |title=Interior View of the Apollo 13 Lunar Module and the 'Mailbox' |work=Great Images in NASA (GRIN) |publisher=NASA |date=April 14, 1970 |id=NASA photo ID: [http://science.ksc.nasa.gov/mirrors/images/images/pao/AS13/10075507.htm AS13-62-8929]; GRIN DataBase Number: GPN-2002-000056 |accessdate=July 3, 2013}}</ref>

Another problem to be solved for a safe return was accomplishing a complete power-up from scratch of the completely shut-down Command Module, something never intended to be done in-flight. Flight controller [[John Aaron]], with the support of grounded astronaut Mattingly and many engineers and designers, had to invent a new procedure to do this with the ship's limited power supply and time factor.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Leopold |first=George |date=March 17, 2009 |title=Power engineer: Video interview with Apollo astronaut Ken Mattingly |journal=[[EE Times]] |publisher=UMB Tech |url=http://eetimes.com/electronics-news/4081844/Power-engineer-Video-interview-with-Apollo-astronaut-Ken-Mattingly |accessdate=August 14, 2010}}</ref> This was further complicated by the fact that the reduced power levels in the LM caused internal temperatures to drop to as low as 40 °F (4 °C). The un-powered CM got so cold that water began to [[Condensation|condense]] on solid surfaces, causing concern that this might short out electrical systems when it was reactivated. This turned out not to be a problem, partly because of the extensive electrical insulation improvements instituted after the [[Apollo 1]] fire.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nasa.gov/mission_pages/constellation/main/A13_panel.html |title=Generation Constellation Learns about Apollo 13 |last=Siceloff |first=Steven |date=September 20, 2007 |work=[[Constellation program|Constellation Program]] |publisher=NASA |accessdate=December 31, 2012}}</ref>

===Re-entry and splashdown===
[[File:Apollo13 - SM after separation.jpg|thumb|left|Apollo 13's damaged [[Apollo Command/Service Module#Service Module (SM)|Service Module]], as photographed from the [[Apollo Command/Service Module#Command Module (CM)|Command Module]] after being jettisoned]]
[[File:Apollo 13 Lunar Module.jpg|thumb|The Apollo 13 Lunar Module ''Aquarius'' is jettisoned above the Earth after serving as a lifeboat for four days. It reentered Earth's atmosphere over [[Fiji]] and burned up]]
[[File:Apollo13.jpg|thumb|250px|The crew of Apollo 13 on board the [[USS Iwo Jima (LPH-2)|USS ''Iwo Jima'']] following splashdown]]
As Apollo 13 neared Earth, the crew first jettisoned the Service Module so pictures could be taken for later analysis. It was then that the crew were surprised to see for the first time that the Sector-4 panel had been blown off. According to the analysts, these pictures also showed the antenna damage and possibly an upward tilt to the fuel cell shelf above the oxygen tank compartment.

[[File:Apollo13 splashdown.jpg|thumb|300px|Apollo 13 splashes down in the South Pacific on April 17, 1970]]
Finally, the crew jettisoned the Lunar Module ''Aquarius'', leaving the Command Module ''Odyssey'' to begin its lone re-entry through the atmosphere. The re-entry on a lunar mission normally was accompanied by about four minutes of typical communications blackout caused by ionization of the air around the Command Module. The blackout in Apollo 13's reentry lasted six minutes, which was 87 seconds longer than had been expected.<ref>{{cite news |title=Did Ron Howard exaggerate the reentry scene in the movie Apollo 13? |first=Joe |last=Pappalardo |url=http://www.airspacemag.com/need-to-know/NEED-Apollo13.html |work=[[Air & Space/Smithsonian]] |publisher=[[Smithsonian Institution]] |location=Washington, D.C. |date=May 1, 2007 |accessdate=March 11, 2013}}</ref> The possibility of heat-shield damage from the {{chem|O|2}} tank rupture heightened the tension of the blackout period.

However, ''Odyssey'' regained radio contact and splashed down safely in the South Pacific Ocean, {{Coord|21|38|24|S|165|21|42|W|type:event|name=Apollo 13 splashdown}}, southwest of [[American Samoa]] and {{convert|6.5|km|mi|abbr=on}} from the recovery ship, [[USS Iwo Jima (LPH-2)|USS ''Iwo Jima'']].
The crew was in good condition except for Haise, who was suffering from a serious [[urinary tract infection]] because of insufficient water intake. To avoid altering the trajectory of the spacecraft, the crew had been instructed to temporarily stop urine dumps. A misunderstanding prompted the crew to store all urine for the rest of the flight.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Lovell |first=James A. |editor-last=Cortright |editor-first=Edgar M. |title=Apollo Expeditions to the Moon |url=http://history.nasa.gov/SP-350/cover.html |accessdate=July 4, 2013 |year=1975 |publisher=NASA |location=Washington, D.C. |id=NASA SP-350 |chapter=Tired, Hungry, Wet, Cold, Dehydrated |chapterurl=http://history.nasa.gov/SP-350/ch-13-5.html}}</ref>

